<font color="#FF0000">LET US HONOR OUR OWN</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 12 13:52:31 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
To a regular Grunt-NAM Vet,<br><br>
There are many missions and places that we went and just don't exist on paper.  I have sorties and airmedals that don't exist for me that were awarded to men on my wing because they could officially be there and I couldn't.  I flew in Laos many times and couldn’t log the sortie.  No flying time.  Not even toward what we flyers call the gate time which had a great deal to do with promotion.<br><br>
I have flown missions that were 300 miles deeper than my backup and they receive silver stars and no mention of me.  It was just our business and we were told that up front.  We expected this treatment not necessarily agreed with it.<br><br>
We received the Expeditionary Medal for going those strange places.  A Medal that has no clusters.<br><br>
The world is full of these political problems especially NAM.  Who really cares if it is MOH or CMH.  The acts that men performed are what they are proud of.  I am sure what Ed said was taken by most the way it was meant.  To be put in for a Medal of Honor is a way of describing the situation.<br><br>
I know of one who was awarded the Navy Cross and recommended for court martial by his service.  They struck a deal.  No Navy Cross and no court martial.  He wasn't where he was supposed to be.<br><br>
Don't miss Ed's point.  It is a greater honor to receive the love of a man for your deed than the highest medal in the land.<br><br>
The Medal of Honor is not taken lightly by this old soldier nor is the situation that justified nomination.  To be nominated usually justified the Silver Star at minimum not just a wipe off the record.  After the war medals was political posturing, certainly not an answer for Ed.<br><br>

<p><code>--   (SW) </code><p>


